Variables and objects

Define some variables

my_var <- 8

Let’s make another variable

my_var2 <- 10

Make a vector

Make our first vector

my_vect <- c(my_var, my_var2)

Let’s make some other vectors

v1 <- c(10, 2, 8, 7, 11, 15)

pets <- c("cat", "dog", "rabbit", "pig")

Make vectors of numbers based on a sequence of numbers

v2 <- 1:10
v3 <- seq(from = 1, to = 10)

Exploring variable elements

Introduce the bracket notation – []

pets
## [1] "cat"    "dog"    "rabbit" "pig"
pets <- c(pets, "snake")
pets
## [1] "cat"    "dog"    "rabbit" "pig"    "snake"
pets[1]
## [1] "cat"
pets[3]
## [1] "rabbit"
# getting number of elements in a sequence
pets[3:4]
## [1] "rabbit" "pig"
# getting number of elements, not in a sequenc
pets[c(1,4)]
## [1] "cat" "pig"
pets
## [1] "cat"    "dog"    "rabbit" "pig"    "snake"

Fun with vectors

mixed_vect <- c(1, 7, "cat")
mixed_vect
## [1] "1"   "7"   "cat"
as.numeric(mixed_vect[1]) + 5
## [1] 6

Indexing matrices

my_mat <- matrix(data = 1:9, nrow = 3, byrow = TRUE)
my_mat
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    1    2    3
## [2,]    4    5    6
## [3,]    7    8    9
my_mat[1]
## [1] 1
my_mat[3]
## [1] 7
my_mat[6]
## [1] 8
# always goes by row, column
my_mat[1,1]
## [1] 1
my_mat[3,2]
## [1] 8
my_mat[1:2, 3]
## [1] 3 6
my_mat[c(1,3), 3]
## [1] 3 9
my_mat[c(1,3), c(1,3)]
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    1    3
## [2,]    7    9
my_mat[1:2, ]
##      [,1] [,2] [,3]
## [1,]    1    2    3
## [2,]    4    5    6

Data Visualization

Get a new package called ggplot2

install.packages("ggplot2")
library(ggplot2)

Visualizing the measurements of a single variable

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Petal.Length)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

x-y scatter plot

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Sepal.Length, y = Petal.Length,
                        colour = Species)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") + 
  xlab("Sepal Length (cm)") +
  ylab("Petal Length (cm)") +
  theme_minimal()

Boxplots

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Species, y = Petal.Length,
                        fill = Species)) +
  geom_boxplot()

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Species, y = Petal.Length,
                        fill = Species)) +
  geom_violin()

Return to histograms

ggplot(data = iris, aes(x = Petal.Length, fill = Species)) +
  #geom_histogram(position = "dodge")
  geom_density(alpha = 0.3)
